---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const updated = new Date('2026-05-27');
const fmt = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' });
---

<Base title="Now — Suryakant Kashyap" description="What I'm working on right now. A snapshot, not a roadmap.">
  <article class="prose-post">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight mb-3">Now</h1>
    <p class="font-sans text-sm text-[color:var(--color-ink-faint)] mb-10">
      Updated {fmt.format(updated)} · <a href="https://nownownow.com/about">about /now pages</a>
    </p>

    <h2>At work</h2>
    <p>
      Shipping the configdb-driven metric shaping + derived metrics work at <a href="https://www.kloudfuse.com/">Kloudfuse</a> — the metrics infrastructure half of the day job. The server-side and rule manager pieces are merged; the admin UI, docs, and a follow-up "Drop preview on the list view" UX improvement are in flight. On the AI side, thinking about what an LLM-driven onboarding assistant for the product would look like — given the cost of generating PromQL has dropped 10× since AIDA, the bar is moving.
    </p>

    <h2>What I'm reading</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Eval-harness papers and post-mortems — how teams actually catch regressions when they swap models. Most of the public writing is still surprisingly thin here.</li>
      <li>The Pinot codebase — specifically the rollup planner and the per-segment query path.</li>
      <li>Anthropic, Cloudflare and the OpenAI cookbook on RAG patterns — comparing the gap between what was hard in 2023 and what's a one-liner now.</li>
      <li>A re-read of <em>Database Internals</em> (Petrov), now with more context about column stores.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What I'm writing</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Slowly turning this site from a content dump into something that feels like a real long-form home for both halves of the work — the AI and the systems.</li>
      <li>A planned follow-up to the AIDA post: what the same prototype would look like if I built it today, and where the actual hard parts live in 2026.</li>
      <li>A planned post on PromQL rollup-table planning — how a query engine decides which resolution to read from, and the failure modes when it picks wrong.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Off-keyboard</h2>
    <p>
      Walking a lot. Trying to maintain a single espresso pour I'm actually proud of. Otherwise quiet.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
